{"type":"message-part","timestamp":"2026-06-12T07:47:26.311Z","messageId":"c6aeeb63-53cf-4c5f-b0f8-c0b87b160307","role":"user","index":1,"part":{"type":"text","text":"# Cars Efficiency Bar Chart with Calculate + Filter Transforms in Vega-Altair\n\n## Background\n\nUsing the classic `cars` dataset, build a Vega-Altair bar chart that derives a per-row fuel-economy efficiency metric inside the chart spec, removes degenerate rows with a server-side filter, and then summarizes the result by engine size. The chart must be saved as a static HTML file that fully renders in a browser.\n\n## Requirements\n\n* Use `data.cars.url` from `vega_datasets` as the data source (URL-based source; declare encoding types explicitly).\n* Inside the chart spec, derive a new field `Efficiency` equal to `Miles_per_Gallon / Weight_in_lbs` using `transform_calculate`.\n* Drop rows where the derived `Efficiency` is not strictly greater than `0.01` using `transform_filter` (the filter must reference the derived `Efficiency` field, not the raw input fields).\n* Build a single `mark_bar` chart that summarizes the filtered data:\n  * The x channel must encode `Cylinders` as an ordinal field, sorted ascending.\n  * The y channel must encode the mean of `Efficiency` as a quantitative field, with an axis title that contains \"Mean Efficiency\" (for example, `\"Mean Efficiency (mpg/lb)\"`).\n  * The color channel must encode `Cylinders` as an ordinal field using the `category10` color scheme.\n* Save the resulting chart as a single self-contained HTML file using `chart.save(...)`.\n\n## Implementation Hints\n\n* Build a single `alt.Chart(data.cars.url)` and chain `transform_calculate(...)` then `transform_filter(...)` before `.mark_bar().encode(...)`.\n* Inside `transform_calculate`, the expression string must reference fields via `datum.<field>` (for example, `'datum.Miles_per_Gallon / datum.Weight_in_lbs'`), and the keyword name passed to `transform_calculate` (or the `as` field of the underlying transform) determines the output field name.\n* Inside `transform_filter`, you can reference the derived field with `alt.datum.Efficiency > 0.01`.\n* Use the method-based `alt.Y(...).axis(title=...)` / `alt.Color(...).scale(scheme=...)` syntax (or the equivalent keyword form) to set the y-axis title and the color scheme.\n* Because the data source is a URL, types must be declared explicitly (`:O`, `:Q`, etc.).\n* Useful references:\n  * https://altair-viz.github.io/user_guide/transform/calculate.html\n  * https://altair-viz.github.io/user_guide/transform/filter.html\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n* Project path: /home/user/myproject\n* Command: python3 build\\_chart.py\n* The command must produce `/home/user/myproject/chart.html` containing a renderable Vega-Lite specification.\n* The embedded Vega-Lite specification must:\n  * Have a top-level `mark` of `bar` (string `\"bar\"` or an object with `type == \"bar\"`).\n  * Include a `transform` array containing both:\n    * a `calculate` entry whose expression references both `Miles_per_Gallon` and `Weight_in_lbs`, and whose `as` field equals `Efficiency`.\n    * a `filter` entry whose filter expression references the `Efficiency` field and the threshold `0.01` (greater-than).\n  * Encode `encoding.x` with `field == \"Cylinders\"`, ordinal type, and ascending sort.\n  * Encode `encoding.y` with `aggregate == \"mean\"`, `field == \"Efficiency\"`, quantitative type, and an axis title containing the substring `\"Mean Efficiency\"`.\n  * Encode `encoding.color` with `field == \"Cylinders\"`, ordinal type, and a color scale with `scheme == \"category10\"`.\n* Browser verification: Loading `chart.html` in a browser must render the chart with no JavaScript console errors; the rendered chart must visibly show one bar per distinct cylinder count from the filtered dataset."}}
